          "verdict": "findings_remain",
          "findings": [
            {
              "message": "`format_generic_args_with_canon_occ` consumes the shared `cursor` while formatting each constraint, then sorts `constraint_parts` afterward. That makes the occurrence numbering depend on the original constraint order, so two semantically identical generic-arg lists that differ only by constraint order can stringify differently and compare unequal even though the final rendering is normalized.",
              "severity": "P1",
              "file": "libs/infrastructure/src/tddd/signal_evaluator_v2/format.rs",
              "line": 602,
              "category": "correctness"
            }
          ],
          "hash": "rvw1:sha256:cf23a0d4a0b8186f5c0740f9d8972dd298829ecc4fac7ac6195fa5685ab9ddc3",
          "at": "2026-05-25T08:28:55Z"
        },
        {
          "type": "fast",
          "verdict": "zero_findings",
          "findings": [],
          "hash": "rvw1:sha256:1d6d7bc5381894bb1b7dcdf5c97318d6ff9cc340cd689f34279207898ccd1541",
          "at": "2026-05-25T08:40:31Z"
        },
        {
          "type": "fast",
          "verdict": "findings_remain",
          "findings": [
            {
              "message": "`Type::DynTrait` now renders each bound before calling `sort_unstable()`, so the shared impl-Trait cursor is consumed in source order rather than canonical order. If two equivalent trait-object bounds contain nested `impl Trait`/synthetic generic args, reordering the bounds changes which occurrence gets `#0` vs `#1`, and semantically identical types can compare unequal.",
              "severity": "P1",
              "file": "/home/flip451/individual/t-rust/templates/SoTOHE-core/libs/infrastructure/src/tddd/signal_evaluator_v2/format.rs",
              "line": 482,
